Package as a Native App. Add multi-account org-level views. Build the what-if simulator. Replace all remaining string-interpolated SQL with Snowpark DataFrame API or parameterized statements. Add proper row access policies. Build a design system. Put it on the Marketplace.

What I Genuinely Dislike (Round 3)
The list is shorter than before. The author has been methodically addressing criticisms, which is itself impressive. But:

Detection without delivery is still the elephant. Three review rounds and the fundamental gap hasn't closed: alerts fire into a table that nobody reads at 2am. webhook_delivery.sql is sitting right there. Wire it in. This is the difference between a monitoring dashboard and a monitoring system.

The incident timeline at tier="recent" will become a performance problem. Joining ALERT_EVENTS + TASK_HISTORY + QUERY_HISTORY (DDL filter) for 7 days, cached for only 5 minutes, executed every time someone opens Control Room. When the new OPS_SLOW_RENDER rule fires, Control Room will likely be the page it fires on. The irony will not be lost on anyone.

FEATURES.md is a band-aid for discoverability, not a solution. The real problem is that the app has 57+ features spread across 8 pages. A manual feature index that says "two review rounds missed shipped features" is an admission that the app's own UI fails to communicate its capabilities. The fix isn't a markdown file — it's better in-app progressive disclosure, contextual help, or an onboarding flow.

The governance drift weights are still hardcoded while platform score weights are now configurable. This inconsistency means one score can be tuned by operators and the other can't. Apply the same pattern.

Net Assessment
Three rounds, and the trajectory is clear: 68 → 76 → 80. Each round addresses the most critical findings from the prior round, and the fixes are architecturally sound rather than cosmetic. The scan decomposition in V017 is the kind of change that separates "someone who builds dashboards" from "someone who operates production systems." The incident timeline is the kind of feature that makes Datadog users say "oh, we need that."

The remaining gap is narrow: delivery, closed-loop workflow, and packaging. Those are product decisions, not engineering deficiencies. The engineering is now solid.
